nodes.title:
{
  "description": "The Tea Act, passed by Parliament earlier that year (1773), granted the British East India Company a significant monopoly on tea sales in the American colonies, which colonial assemblies and merchants viewed as a direct challenge to their economic autonomy and rights.",
  "type": "triggering",
  "date": "1773"
}

{
  "description": "On December 16, 1773, American colonists, some disguised as Mohawk Indians, boarded British ships anchored in Boston Harbor and purposefully threw 342 chests of British tea overboard into the water as a dramatic act of protest.",
  "type": "intermediate",
  "date": "1773-12-16"
}

{
  "description": "In 1774, the British government responded swiftly and harshly to the Boston Tea Party by enacting a series of punitive measures known as the Coercive Acts, designed to punish Massachusetts and reassert imperial authority over the colonies.",
  "type": "outcome",
  "date": "1774"
}

{
  "description": "The British Parliament's Tea Act directly caused the Boston Tea Party because its grant of a monopoly to the British East India Company was perceived by American colonists as an unjust violation of their economic freedom and rights, prompting a forceful, public act of defiance.",
  "status": "supported"
}

{
  "description": "The Boston Tea Party served as a powerful demonstration that American colonists were prepared and willing to engage in significant, direct, and overtly destructive actions against British policies that they deemed fundamentally unjust and oppressive, signaling escalating resistance.",
  "status": "supported"
}

{
  "description": "The British government's swift and harsh punitive response to the Boston Tea Party, specifically the enactment of the Coercive Acts of 1774, paradoxically further united colonial opposition across the various colonies against British rule rather than quelling dissent.",
  "status": "supported"
}

